<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-449-953  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 449 953.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Sept 24 1990 n319 p48(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Computer danger. (Computer crimes)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Knack, Kella.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Contrary to popular belief, computer hackers are not the maincause of security damages and breaches, a new report states.andO;Corporate Computer Security Issues and Strategies states thatemployees are to blame for about 80 percent of these breaches.andO;The employees are unaware most times of their mistakes.andP;  There arefive types of employees who commit these breaches.andP;  They consistof disenchanted or former employees, ignorant employees,consultant or contract programmers, competitors engaged inindustrial espionage and external hackers.andP;  The most dangerous arethe disgruntled employees because of the malice associated withtheir actions.andP;  The report suggests that these employees caneasily resort to sabotage if they are not dealt with in time.andP;  Oneway to handle the problem is for supervisors to deal withemployees' complaints before it reaches a crisis stage.andP;  Also,employee passwords and access codes should be taken away when anemployee leaves a company.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     SecurityComputer CrimesNetwork Operating SystemsAccess ControlsAccess MethodsData ManagementPersonnel Problems.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Types of computer crimes. (graph)Biometric technologies in use in 1989. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>